<DocsLayout title="Mod compatibility" description="How etmc coexists with other mods, including ViaFabricPlus.">
  <p>etmc is built to stay out of the way of other mods, including protocol-translation mods like
    <strong>ViaFabricPlus</strong>.</p>

  <h2>Why it composes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Thin, transport-level mixins.</strong> etmc only swaps the connection's transport and tweaks
      the multiplayer screens — it never touches packet handling.</li>
    <li><strong>Below the protocol.</strong> Connections are carried at the raw byte level — a custom netty
      channel on the mesh for <code>etmc://</code> links, or a loopback relay for the code and config-URL
      paths — <em>below</em> the Minecraft protocol. ViaFabricPlus translates in the client's netty pipeline
      and etmc carries the already-translated bytes verbatim, so the two stack cleanly.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Auto version detection</h2>
  <p>
    ViaFabricPlus figures out a server's version by opening its own probe to the server address. Whether that
    works depends on the join path:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Join with a code / config URL.</strong> These ride a loopback relay, so ViaFabricPlus's probe
      passes straight through to the host and auto-detect just works — nothing special needed.</li>
    <li><strong><code>etmc://</code> links.</strong> These use the mesh netty channel directly, so there is no
      socket for ViaFabricPlus to probe and its auto-detect can't reach the host on its own. etmc detects the
      host's protocol itself — a status ping over the mesh — and pins it onto the server entry through
      ViaFabricPlus's forced-version API, so VFP translates without probing. No dependency on ViaFabricPlus:
      if it isn't installed, etmc simply skips this.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Stable loopback port</h2>
  <p>
    On the code / config-URL paths, ViaFabricPlus stores per-server settings by address. Set
    <code>joinLocalPort</code> in <code>config/etmc.json</code> to a fixed port so a forced version persists
    across sessions (default <code>0</code> = ephemeral; etmc falls back to ephemeral if the port is taken).
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
